00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:47.430
So, a useful guiding idea is that mathematical&nbsp;
definitions should be concise, clear, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.430 --> 00:01:54.510
close to specifications. I mean the information&nbsp;
required to determine a particular mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.510 --> 00:02:02.160
object. To illustrate that, let's look at&nbsp;
a triangle. Alright, so here's a triangle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:07.740
and let's think about the question of&nbsp;
how to define what a triangle is. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.740 --> 00:02:11.670
is a question that's finessed in almost&nbsp;
all geometry books, rather amazingly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.570 --> 00:02:16.950
even though a triangle is an absolutely&nbsp;
fundamental mathematical object. Somehow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.950 --> 00:02:22.920
people think it's not necessary to define what it&nbsp;
is exactly. Well, I think it is very important to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:30.810
define exactly what it is. And for me, a triangle&nbsp;
is a set of three points that are not collinear.

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:39.690
But there are also other possibilities. You&nbsp;
could also define a triangle as a set of three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:47.430
line segments. The line segments have the property&nbsp;
that they're meeting at the corners. Or you could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:50.610
define a triangle in terms of three lines
𝐿&nbsp;

