00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:10.320
I'm not saying that these are wrong. These&nbsp;
are all legitimate variants on possibilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:14.310
But there's something a little bit more&nbsp;
efficient about this one than these three.

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:20.760
Suppose, for example, that we have a particular&nbsp;
triangle in mind that we want to send the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:26.940
information to specify that particular&nbsp;
triangle to our friend on the Internet. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:32.190
we can't draw a picture; we just want to send&nbsp;
some amount of data. With this description,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.190 --> 00:03:35.460
we need to send the coordinates&nbsp;
of this point, this point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:43.710
and this point—two pieces of data each will&nbsp;
specify this triangle. With this approach,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:43.710 --> 00:03:50.310
we need to specify the three line segments. To&nbsp;
specify a line segment requires two endpoints. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:56.310
we have two coordinates per endpoint, but each one&nbsp;
of these endpoints is itself a point, so we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.310 --> 00:04:03.270
six times two: twelve pieces of information&nbsp;
to specify the triangle via line segments.

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:08.354
Via lines, well, if we think&nbsp;
of a line as being a triple&nbsp;

00:04:08.354 --> 00:04:08.359
