00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:16.110
nine pieces of information required there. And&nbsp;
there's also a little bit of ambiguity because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.110 --> 00:04:22.080
lines are only defined up to scalars. And I think&nbsp;
we want to define this. Well, it's not so clear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:26.670
how you're going to define that as a region&nbsp;
or how you're going to express that region by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:32.910
doing one of these three things and talking about&nbsp;
the region inside, given a situation like this.

00:04:32.910 --> 00:04:41.190
So, my point here is that if you have to define&nbsp;
a new mathematical object—let's say you've just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.190 --> 00:04:46.200
discovered a squiggle, and this is a new idea&nbsp;
that you want to introduce to mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:51.210
and you have an intuitive idea of what a squiggle&nbsp;
is—but you would like to make a clear mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:57.210
definition. So, my suggestion to you is to ask&nbsp;
yourself the following question: Suppose I have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.210 --> 00:05:02.610
a particular squiggle, whatever it is, and I&nbsp;
want to convey that information to somebody&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:09.030
else via the Internet. What is the minimal&nbsp;
amount of information that I have to compose&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:15.090
to be able to completely specify the squiggle?&nbsp;
You have to think about the most efficient way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.090 --> 00:05:22.290
of encoding that information and then try to make&nbsp;
your definition as close to that specification as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.290 --> 00:05:28.560
possible. When specifications and definitions are&nbsp;
close together, then you have a pleasant theory.

00:05:28.560 --> 00:05:36.360
Now, let's talk a little bit about the&nbsp;
interpretation of mathematical definitions. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:45.330
mathematical definitions can be visualized&nbsp;
or interpreted or modeled in different ways.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.330 --> 00:05:50.940
This is an interesting idea with a lot of&nbsp;
ramifications. So, let me try to explain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:57.960
it through a very simple example. When we&nbsp;
defined a point originally, we were thinking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:05.370
and I drew a picture of a plane and a dot, and&nbsp;
I said, "That's the point," and we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:12.720
describe or define what that point is. And&nbsp;
we decided on an ordered pair to denote the&nbsp;

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:13.320
𝑥
x and the&nbsp;

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:14.190
𝑦
y coordinates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:18.180
used to specify that point. That was&nbsp;
our definition of a point, and that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:22.560
was our visualization. It represents&nbsp;
a dot in this two-dimensional plane.

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:29.940
But some people might object to this definition.&nbsp;
The definition of an ordered pair without a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.940 --> 00:06:36.420
diagram seems to be completely divorced from&nbsp;
the geometry. You can't necessarily tell what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:45.630
the geometry is. That's actually a good thing&nbsp;
because it gives us flexibility in interpreting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.630 --> 00:06:54.600
what our mathematics is really about. It turns out&nbsp;
that there's more than one way often of modeling&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.600 --> 00:07:01.530
or interpreting a given mathematical expression&nbsp;
or formula or result. So, to give you an example&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:06.180
of some alternatives, here's a different&nbsp;
picture that also models the idea of a point.

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:08.310
So, now I've taken this&nbsp;

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:09.024
𝑥
x-&nbsp;

00:07:09.024 --> 00:07:11.550
